From: Parsec Web <patches@parsec.os>
Date: 2026-02-17
Subject: [PATCH 7/9] Parsec Mid-Tier JIT (PMJ) — Maglev equivalent for JSC

Background: Why Maglev Exists
──────────────────────────────
V8's tier stack:
  Ignition (interpreter) → Sparkplug (baseline) → Maglev (mid) → Turbofan (top)

JSC's tier stack before this patch:
  LLInt → Baseline JIT → DFG → FTL

The gap between Baseline and DFG in JSC is large. DFG is a full SSA-form
optimizing compiler — expensive to compile. For medium-hot functions (called
hundreds of times, not millions), DFG overkill slows compilation and medium-hot
code runs at Baseline speed longer than it should.

Maglev fills this gap in V8 by doing:
  1. Type specialization from inline cache feedback
  2. Unboxing of known-integer/double values
  3. Simple inlining of small callees
  4. Linear scan register allocation (fast to compile, good enough codegen)

This patch adds "Parsec Mid-Tier JIT" (PMJ) to JSC with identical goals.
PMJ sits between Baseline and DFG:
  LLInt → Baseline → PMJ → DFG → FTL

PMJ compilation triggers at ~300 invocations (vs DFG at 500 after patch 0006).
DFG threshold raised to 8000 — functions spend quality time in PMJ then
graduate to DFG only when truly worth the compilation cost.

Architecture of PMJ
────────────────────
PMJ takes Baseline JIT's bytecode profile + inline cache data and emits
optimized machine code using a linear IR (no SSA, no PHI nodes — that's
DFG's job). Key optimizations PMJ performs:

  1. Integer unboxing — if IC data says a value is always int32, emit
     unboxed integer arithmetic instead of JSValue boxing/unboxing.
     This alone gives 2-4x on integer-heavy loops.

  2. Double unboxing — same for floating point. Math.sin() loops, physics,
     animation frames go from boxed-double to native FP register ops.

  3. Monomorphic call specialization — if a call site has seen only one
     callee shape, emit a direct call with a guard instead of a
     polymorphic dispatch. V8 Maglev does exactly this.

  4. Property access specialization — if a property access has seen only
     one structure, emit a direct offset load with a structure guard.
     Eliminates the IC lookup on the hot path.

  5. Linear scan register allocation — assigns virtual registers to
     physical registers in one forward pass. O(n) vs DFG's O(n log n).
     Compiles 5-10x faster than DFG for equivalent code quality on
     medium-complexity functions.

  6. OSR entry from Baseline — a running Baseline function can be
     replaced mid-execution by PMJ (like V8 OSR). Hot loops don't
     wait for the function to return.

